Defendant Lamar McNutt in court with attorney Michael Jude.  Zachary A Wittchow for Danielle Chojnacki appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  

The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 12 MONTHS at the House of Corrections with 2 days credit CONCURRENT to any other sentence.  STRAIGHT TIME.

Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on 2 YEARS probation.

  Conditions of Probation:
- 5 MONTHS condition time Huber & Day Reporting Center.  Court stayed commencement until 04/04/2016 by 5pm.
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute/maintain sobriety, no alcohol, no drugs.
- No possession/consumption/selling/distribution of illegal drugs/alcohol.
- Random urine screens.
- Obtain/maintain fulltime employment/education/vocation.
- Provide a DNA sample.
- Follow all rules of supervision and follow through with any other treatment deemed necessary by the department.

Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
All court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA); 
All applicable fees of supervision.
-  Cash bail on deposit to be applied if applicable.

At the request of the defense, and without objection from the court or the state, sentencing is moved from 03/17/2016 at 8:30am to 04/01/2016 at 8:30am.  Defendant to check in on 03/17/2016 at 8:30am to receive new date.

Defendant Lamar McNutt in court with attorney Michael Jude.  Danielle Chojnacki appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Case in court for jury trial, however parties would like to proceed with a plea hearing instead.    Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  Case is adjourned for sentencing in Branch 22.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for March 17, 2016 at 08:30 am.
